# MBTA-57-bus[MBTA-57-bus README.md](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/24597421/MBTA-57-bus.README.md)
**Project Description:**

* This project gives a detailed analysis of the 57 bus line from Watertown Yard to Kenmore station. The project first determines the stops and each of their IDs so they can be used to find both the predicted departure and arrival times at each stop. This difference between each time is then averaged to get a mean wait time. Statistical analysis then performed across all this data to get overall statistics and trends for average wait times across all stations.

**Instructions:**

* This game requires Python 3, requests, pandas, numpy, matplotlib, datetime, math, statistics and ipython. Install these if needed using the command: pip install requests pandas numpy matplotlib datetime math statistics ipython  
* Open the .py file in a program or notebook that can run Python.  
* If you are running the program in a notebook, run all cells.

**Challenges Encountered:**

* Find out the name of each stop and the stop ID individually seemed like it would be tedious. To solve this we created lists of each stop and each stop's ID and also merged them into a dictionary for easy ID access.  
* When creating the list of times for the arrivals/departures of the buses, we found out that there are multiple predicted times for each stop. Needed to find a way to associate all of the predicted times with the same stop which was done through creating two different listsâ€”one (a sublist) that kept track of all times for each stop, then the overall list that had the list of sublists  
* When looking at the data called through the API, we found that some departure times were predicted to happen before the arrival times. When we googled why this was happening, it said it might just have to do with the way the MBTA collects data. This was a challenge because for our original plan, we wanted to define "wait time" as the time between the bus's departure at a stop and the next bus's arrival at the same stop. However, due to the data provided and our inability to correct it, we used time between departures as wait time.  
* The conclusions and data visualizations provided about are based on a certain API call, but it is likely that these conclusions would be different if the API was called at another time.

**Conclusions:**

* By calculating the average wait times of each inbound and outbound stop, we determined that the mean wait time across all inbound stops was about 17 minutes and the mean wait time across all outbound stops was about 15 minutes and 42 seconds.  
* To determine the median wait time, we used statistics.median to determine that the median wait time across all inbound stops was about 15 minutes and 28 seconds and the median wait time across all outbound stops was 12 minutes and 30 seconds.   
* To determine the standard deviation we used the numpy.std command to determine that the standard deviation for wait times among inbound stops was about 9 minutes and the standard deviation for wait times among outbound stops was 13 minutes and 30 seconds.   
* The histograms show the distribution of average wait times for the inbound and outbound routes. They show that the majority of inbound stops have an average wait time of 15-20 minutes, and the outbound stops have an average wait time of 0-15 minutes.   
* In order to determine the inbound and outbound stops that are the busiest, we used the bar graph to search for the stops with the least amount of wait time as this means the stop was the most frequented. Looking at the graph for inbound stops, Brighton Ave at Cambridge Street had the least wait time and for outbound stops, there was a tie between the stops for Tremont Street at Boylston stations, Stuart Street at Charles Street South and Saint James Avenue at Arlington Street.
